Dear Team,

As part of our migration to the new GitLab instance (gitlab.sbi), we have rolled out a standardized set of governance rules across all SBIePay application repositories. These rules are now LIVE. Please read this carefully before your next push or merge request, as your existing habits from the old GitLab may now be rejected.

====================================================
1. BRANCH NAMING — enforced on branch creation
====================================================
Branches that do not match the approved pattern will be REJECTED on push. Allowed branch names:

  main
  develop
  release/<major>.<minor>.<patch>     e.g. release/1.5.0
  feature/EPAY-<id>-<short-desc>        e.g. feature/EPAY-1234-upi-autopay
  bugfix/EPAY-<id>-<short-desc>         e.g. bugfix/EPAY-1299-fix-mandate
  hotfix/<major>.<minor>.<patch>        e.g. hotfix/1.5.1

Rules:
 - Use lowercase letters, numbers, and hyphens only in the description part.
 - feature and bugfix branches MUST include the EPAY Jira ID.
 - release and hotfix branches use the version number (no description).

WILL BE REJECTED:
  feature/login                (missing EPAY id)
  feature/EPAY-123-Add_Login    (uppercase + underscore)
  release/1.5                  (not full X.Y.Z)
  my-test-branch               (not an approved type)

====================================================
2. COMMIT MESSAGES — enforced on every commit
====================================================
Format:  <type>(<scope>): <subject> EPAY-<id>

 - <type> is one of: feat, fix, docs, style, refactor, perf, test, chore
 - <scope> is optional, lowercase, in parentheses
 - <subject> must be 10 to 100 characters
 - The message MUST end with the EPAY Jira ID

VALID examples:
  feat(auth): add login flow for users EPAY-123
  fix: correct null pointer on refund EPAY-1299
  chore(ci): bump pipeline image version EPAY-42

WILL BE REJECTED:
  update stuff                          (no type, no EPAY id)
  feat: short EPAY-1                     (subject under 10 chars)
  feat(auth): add login flow            (missing EPAY id)

Tip: configure a local commit template so you don't forget the format.

====================================================
3. PROTECTED BRANCHES — no direct push
====================================================
main, develop, and release/* are protected. You CANNOT push to them directly. All changes must arrive via a Merge Request that passes approvals and the pipeline.

 - main      : merge by Bank App Maintainer / Owner only
 - develop   : merge by Vendor App Lead
 - release/* : merge by Vendor App Architect

feature/*, bugfix/*, and hotfix/* remain open for you to push freely.

====================================================
4. MERGE REQUEST APPROVALS
====================================================
Approvals depend on the TARGET branch:

 - feature or bugfix --> develop : 1 approval (Lead)
 - develop or bugfix --> release/* : 2 approvals (Lead + Architect)
 - release --> main : 4 approvals (Architect + Vendor PM + Bank Maintainer + Bank PM)
 - hotfix --> main : same 4 approvals; hotfix MR description must include the Jira incident ID

The pipeline must pass before any MR can be merged. The source branch is deleted automatically after merge.

====================================================
WHAT YOU NEED TO DO
====================================================
 - Rename any in-progress local branches to match the new pattern before pushing.
 - Adopt the commit message format immediately.
 - Raise MRs instead of pushing to protected branches.

If a push is rejected, the error message will tell you which rule failed. For questions or genuine exceptions, contact the DevSecOps team.

Thank you for helping keep the SBIePay platform audit-compliant.

